@node Weapon proficiencies
@section Weapon proficiencies
@cindex weapon proficiencies
@cindex proficiencies, weapon

Charaters receive weapon proficiencies, when wielding a
weapon the character receive a +1 damage bonus for each
proficiencies level on the wielded weapon. Additionally,
when wielding a weapon without for which the charater lack
a proficiency he receives a −1 damage penalty.

Level 1 fighters, rangers and paladins can assign four
proficiency points, at most two per weapon, other classes
can only assign two points, at most one per weapon. At level
 up a character can sometimes add another proficiency level.
Fighters can at most have 5 in proficiency levels on a
weapon, rangers and paladins can have at most 3, other
classes can atmost have 2 in proficiency levels.

The weapons you can become proficient in depends on which
class you have selected. But there are a total of eight
available proficiency.

@itemize @bullet
@item  Bow
@item  Spiked weapons
@item  Small swords
@item  Large swords
@item  Axe
@item  Blunt weapons
@item  Missile weapons
@item  Pole-arm
@end itemize


@node Thief abilities
@section Thief abilities
@cindex thief abilities

Thieves, both singleclassed and multiclassed, have four
special abilities.

@itemize @bullet
@item  Find traps (5)
(and move disarm them)
@item  Open locks (10)
@item  Pick pockets (15)
@item  Stealth (10)
(move silently/hide in shadows)
@end itemize

Thieves have 30 points allocated at the first level,
indicated by the brackets in the list above, and will
receive 20 additional points to allocate for each level,
including the first level. Rangers also have stealth, and
bards have pick pocket, 5 points per level, starting at 10
and limited to 99. A point is a 1 %-unit unit, that is
multiplied the 1D20 roll.

During stealth mode a character by be successful in
performing a backstab when attacking with melée weapons.
At level 1 to 4 backstab doubles the damage taked by the
target, 3 times at level 5 to 8, 4 times at level 9 to
12, and 5 times at level 13 and higher.

