@section Attack roll
@cindex attack roll
@cindex armour class
@cindex AC
@cindex THAC0
@cindex to hit armour class 0

Three factors decide whether an attack is successful,
neither effects the damage made: armour class (AC),
‘to hit armor class 0’ (THAC0) and attack roll. To
successfully hit a target the attack roll be at least
THAC0 − AC. The attack roll consists of 1D20 roll.

Without any adjustment (including armour) a character's
armour class is 10. The THAC0 depends on the character's
class and level, for each level up the characters receives
a −1 THAC0 bonus.


@node Critical hits and misses
@section Critical hits and misses
@cindex critical hits
@cindex critical misses
@cindex hits, critical
@cindex misses, critical

If a character rolls 20, before modifiers, on his attack
roll, a critical hit occurs and the damage for the attack is
doubled. If the value roll is 1 it is a critical miss, which
is a miss with a time penalty of one round. A critical hit
is always an hit, regardless of armour class and THAC0.


@node Casting spells
@section Casting spells
@cindex casting spells
@cindex spell casting

Spellcasters must memorise spells to be able to use them,
or use them directly from a scroll. Additionally a
spellcaster must be able to speak and may be paralised
or petrified to cast a spell, and the target must be in
sight.


@node Spell disruption
@section Spell disruption
@cindex spell disruption
@cindex disrupting spells

If a spellcaster is damage during a spell casting the spell
will disrupted and the spell memorisation will be lost as it
would be if it was not disrupted. Spells are also disrupted
if the spellcaster performs another action.


@node Hit points
@section Hit points
@cindex hit points

Creatures have a maximum hit point beyond which the creature
cannot be healed. Some necromantic spell increase or
decrease a creatures maximum hit point. It is also increase
when a characters levels up.


@node Natural healing
@section Natural healing
@cindex natural healing

Characters that are not in combat can heal naturally, call
regeneration. This is utilised more effectively during
sleep, specially in comfortable room in an inn.

Sleep cannot always be done indoors, and cannot be done
while there are emenies nearby. Sleeping, except for at
Inns, you run a risk of being attacked.


@node Magical healing
@section Magical healing
@cindex magical healing

Characters, including foes, can use spells, potions and
magical devices to considerably heal themself or other
characters. Healing can other be instant or continuous.


@node Raising the dead
@section Raising the dead
@cindex raising the dead
@cindex resurrection

Dead characters are uneffected by spells other then Raise
Dead and Resurrection. Newly raised characters will have
only on hit point and require addition healing.

A character dies when his hit points reaches zero. If the
character'shit points reached −10 at point of death, the
character is beyond resurrection.

Dead characters, that are resurrectable, will leave a body
item that the other characters must carry to a temple to
resurrect, or to any other place, if they do not wise to
resurrect the character right there.


@node Effects of poison
@section Effects of poison
@cindex effects of poison
@cindex poison

Charaters can be poisoned, their are many sources, poisoned
weapons and ammunition, venomous creatures, potions, bad
food and drugges wines. Poisoned characters will be hurt a
hit point or two every so often; healing spells and potions
will not negate the progress, rather a poison specialised
potion or spell must be used.


@node Effects of paralysis
@section Effects of paralysis
@cindex effects of paralysis
@cindex paralysis

A creature affected by paralysis cannot speak, move, attack,
defend or cast spell during the effect of the spell.


@node Magic resistance
@section Magic resistance
@cindex magic resistance
@cindex resistance against magic

Magic resistance gives a creature a change to ignore the
effect of magic, both protective and destructive magic, but
not priest spells. If the creature fails to utilise magic
resistance, saving throw against that spell can be used.


@node Changing armour
@section Changing armour
@cindex changing armour
@cindex changing body armour

Changing body armour takes two rounds and cannot be done
during combat. Just adding or just removing the armour
takes one round.




