@node The map
@section The map
@cindex map

@cindex locked doors
@cindex doors
@cindex world map
@cindex area map
@cindex major area
The game consists of a world map and and area maps. The
world map is a network of area maps, area maps can contain
other area maps. In an area map there are connections to
other area maps, they may be of another area map in the
world map (a major area), or they may or may not be blocked
by a locked doored. Locked doors can often be opened by
picking or bashing, but sometimes they are opened by quest
events.

When reaching the edge of a major area it is possible that
you can detect new major areas, but sometimes they are only
added to your map by quest events. When going to the edge of
a major area all neighbouring major areas that are in your
map, or detected, become visitable which means that you can
go to it at any time you reach any major area edge.

@cindex area distance
@cindex map area distance
@cindex waylay
Major areas have distances between them which effects how
long it takes for your party to reach the target area.
While traviling there is risk of running into enemies,
which is decided by a die roll depending on the road.
The risk of running into enemies is doubled during the
dark hours.


@node The environment
@section The environment
@cindex environment

@cindex rest
@cindex sleep
Whether you can rest or not depends on the environment,
generally you will be able to rest outdoors but not indoors
(except for rented room). When you rest there is a risk
that your sleep will be interrupted, it can either be by
hostiles or by guards telling you that you man not spell
there and should find an inn.

@cindex items
@cindex hostiles
@cindex creatures
An environment consists of items an creatures. Some items
you can take with you, others are stuck and you can look
inside them for other items, the latter may be locked in the
same way as doors. Creatures have positions and may be
hostile. Hostile creatures may be resurrected when you leave
the area.



@node Dice and modifiers
@chapter Dice and modifiers
@cindex dice
@cindex modifiers

There are two types of modifiers, units and procents. A unit
modifier is added to the outcome of a die roll and procents
are multiplied to the agumented die roll, it usually is less
than 100 %, but can be higher than 100 %.

A die roll is written as the number of dice followed by the
die type, that is the number of sides on the dice prepending
by a `D'. D6 is a regular six-sided die, and 2D6 is two such
dice whose value are added.

This game uses ten different dice. First off, there three
simulated dice, D2, D3 and D100. D2 is simulated by a
dividing a D4's values and round up, D3 works the same way
but uses a D6. D100 is simulated by rolling two separate D10
dice, the first roll times 10 plus the second roll, which
roll with a modulo 10 agument determines the outcome of a
D100 roll. Then there are five plutonic solids, D4, D6, D8,
D12 and D20. Finally there are two non-plutonic solids with
uniform stocastic distribution: D10 and D24.



